ing conversation, the challenges of writing dialogue in fiction, the pros and cons of Zoom, the relationship of conversation to vaudeville acts, and the educational value of a good college seminar where students learn to talk about ideas. Cohen looks at some of the famous groups of writers and artists in history whose conversation fed their creativity, and details some of the habits that can result in bad conversation.Blending the immediacy of a beautifully crafted memoir with the conviviality of an intimate gathering with friends, Talking Cure makes a persuasive case for the civilizing value of conversation and is essential reading for anyone interested in the chatter that fuels culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConversation in literature. 0aConversationxSocial aspects. 0aConversation. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Social.2bisacsh  aAn Essay on the Civilizing Power of Conversation.  aPaula Marantz Cohen.  aPrinceton University Press.  aTalking Cure.  aart of good conversation.  abeautifully crafted memoir.  abooks on talking.  achatter that fuels culture.  acoffee chat.  aconversation.  aexploration of the pleasures.  afriends who listen.  afriendship.  alistening.  aliterature and culture.  ameeting for coffee.  amemoir.  aphilosophy books on converstaions.  aphilosophy of converstaion.  aphilosophy.  apower of conversatio.  apsychological benefits of converstaion.  apublishing.  arole of food and conversation.  asocial benefits of conversation.  asoundboards.  athe benefits of converstaion.  awhy we need to talk.  awhy we talk.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook packa